{"action": "edit", "code": "def translate_red_pixels_to_object_area(input_grid: np.ndarray, output_grid: np.ndarray, object_area: List[int]) -> np.ndarray:\n    \"\"\"\n    This function takes an input grid as a numpy array, an output grid as a numpy array containing only green and black pixels,\n    and a list of four integers representing the area surrounded by the columns and rows where green pixels are in. \n    It returns a new numpy array containing the same green and black pixels as output_grid, but with the red pixels translated\n    to be in the object_area.\n    \n    Args:\n    input_grid: A numpy array representing the input grid\n    output_grid: A numpy array containing only green and black pixels\n    object_area: A list of four integers representing the area surrounded by the columns and rows where green pixels are in\n    \n    Returns:\n    A numpy array containing the same green and black pixels as output_grid, but with the red pixels translated to be in the object_area.\n    \"\"\"\n    rows, cols = np.where(input_grid == red)\n    for i in range(len(rows)):\n        if rows[i] >= object_area[0] and rows[i] <= object_area[1] and (cols[i] >= object_area[2]) and (cols[i] <= object_area[3]):\n            output_grid[rows[i] - object_area[0], cols[i] - object_area[2]] = red\n    return output_grid\ndef main(input_grid: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    object_area = find_green_area(input_grid)\n    output_grid = filter_green_and_black_pixels(input_grid)\n    object_area = [object_area[0] + 1, object_area[1] - 1, object_area[2] + 1, object_area[3] - 1]\n    output_grid = translate_red_pixels_to_object_area(input_grid, output_grid, object_area)\n    return output_grid\ndef find_green_area(input_grid: np.ndarray) -> List[int]:\n    \"\"\"\n    This function takes an input grid as a numpy array and returns a list of four integers representing the area\n    surrounded by the columns and rows where green pixels are in. The list contains the indices of the fi